    hdTitle: "Holistic Dentistry",
    hdTitle1: "What is Holistic Dentistry?",
    hdBio: "Holistic dentistry does not consider the patient's mouth and teeth as an isolated area from the rest of the body. Health problems often do not have their roots at the site of the disorder. For example, a diseased tooth can trigger symptoms in joints. Conversely, mouth ulcers can be caused by food intolerance. In both cases, it is important to expand the scope of diagnostics beyond the site of manifestation of the disease symptom. Chronic diseases in particular require the exhaustion of all diagnostic possibilities. Holistic dentistry has developed diagnostic and therapeutic procedures that allow dentists with holistic training to uncover these relationships. Particular attention is paid to the problem of tooth filling materials and dental materials. The dentist, who works holistically, selects therapies that mean a responsible approach to the patient's health and that take into account the interactions between teeth and organism. His training enables him to also practice homeopathy, oral acupuncture, neural therapy, etc. apply.",
    hdTitle2: "What is Neural Therapy?",
    ntBio: "Neural therapy (according to Huneke) is a holistic therapy and diagnostic procedure that was developed by the German brothers Ferdinand and Walter Huneke around 80 years ago. The self-healing of the organism is initiated by means of targeted injections of a short-acting local anesthetic via the vegetative nervous system.",
    ntTitle1: "What diseases is neural therapy used for?",
    ntBio1: "The indication area covers acute and chronic conditions and thus extends across all medical specialties. The following diseases are treated particularly frequently: back pain (including herniated discs), joint diseases, migraines, neuralgic and postoperative pain, certain infectious diseases (e.g. maxillary sinusitis), prostate diseases, hormonal disorders such as menstrual disorders, dizziness, menopausal symptoms, overactive and underactive thyroid glands.",
    ntTitle2: "What effects does neural therapy have on the organism?",
    ntBio2: `In order to understand the effect of neural therapy, one must know the function of the autonomic nervous system. It is a complex network consisting of millions of the finest nerve fibers. All cells and organs are connected to each other via this information network. It has the task of coordinating and regulating all vital functions. In neural therapy, targeted stimuli are applied and certain nerve connections are interrupted for a short time so that the body has the chance to reorganize itself into a normal state. In this way, even long-standing, chronic illnesses can often be cured. We distinguish between two different therapeutic approaches in neural therapy. On the one hand, there is the local and segmental treatment, as it is often used in conventional medicine. Chronic irritation processes are interrupted by injecting the local anesthetic into the skin, muscles or nerves or nerve switching points. The second approach is the treatment of so-called interference fields. These are misinformations imprinted in the vegetative. They can form anywhere in the body as a result of injury, surgery, inflammation, etc. Interference fields have the property of emitting interference impulses via vegetative nerve fibers, which subsequently lead to symptoms and disorders such as pain in distant places. Typical interference field localizations are tonsils, sinuses, tooth and jaw area, prostate, gynecological area, scars of all kinds and by eliminating an interference field using local anesthetics, the existing "vicious circle" is broken and the healing of the disease is made possible. This effect is particularly impressive in the so-called instantaneous phenomenon, in which a remote disturbance is healed in one second by treating the disturbance field.`,
    ntTitle3: "Are side effects or risks to be expected?",
    ntBio3: "If the injection technique is carried out correctly, neural therapy is an extremely gentle method with few side effects. A slight feeling of dizziness after neural therapy is completely normal and usually only lasts a few minutes. Smaller bruises in the area of the injection sites are possible, but harmless.",
    ntTitle4: "For which patients is neural therapy not suitable?",
    ntBio4: "There are some situations where neural therapy should not be used, such as allergy to the local anesthetic used, but this is very rare. Deeper injections should not be used in patients with a tendency to bleed or who thin the blood. Neural therapy is ineffective for the treatment of cancer and diseases in which tissue has already been destroyed, e.g. cirrhosis of the liver. However, cancer patients can also benefit from neural therapy for the treatment of pain.",
