    ptcTitle1: "What is professional teeth cleaning?",
    ptcBio: "Professional teeth cleaning is a process where the teeth are treated with ultrasound and pigmented with a special powder jet device and then polished. Dental cleaning also includes examining the teeth and gums, and then, if necessary, proper oral hygiene is instructed, especially in areas that are difficult to access, such as under bridges and implants. A so-called recall system is also recommended, in which the patient can be notified of his next recall appointment by letter, email or SMS.",
    ftTitle: "Filling Therapy -Caries",
    ftTitle1: "What is dental caries?",
    ftBio1: "Dental caries (from the Latin caries 'morschheit', 'rottenness'; also tooth decay or tooth decay; medically Caries dentium) is a disease of the hard tooth tissue enamel and dentin.",
    ftTitle2: "What are the early stages of tooth decay?",
    ftBio2: `As a preliminary stage to caries (initial caries), decalcifications form first. These are macroscopically recognizable as white spots (English white spot, Latin macula alba). These spots often become dark (lat. macula fusca) due to the accumulation of color pigments from food.`,
    ftTitle3: "How do you treat early tooth decay?",
    ftBiobjorn1: "Caries, which is only limited to the enamel, does not always have to be treated. As long as the enamel layer is only attacked but still intact overall, the lesion can be remineralized by suitable fluoridation measures and a change in diet (following nutritional advice). The hydroxide ions in the apatite are replaced by fluoride to form fluorapatite.",
    ftTitle4: "How do you recognize early tooth decay?",
    ftBiobjorn2: "If dental caries is in the early stages, i. H. as long as only the enamel (caries superficialis) is affected, not remineralized, it penetrates into the dentin (tooth bone). Even this dentine caries (caries media) can lead to toothache. Since dentin is much softer than enamel, caries spreads out below the enamel-dentin border. The enamel that has been undermined in this way at the edges of the carious defect breaks down after a certain time when chewing. The caries is often noticed for the first time, although it has existed for a long time.",
    ftTitle5: "How do you recognize deep caries?",
    ftBiobjorn3: "Caries profunda (deep dental caries) is present when the caries lesion has progressed so far that more than two thirds of the dentin layer in the direction of the dental pulp (dental pulp) has been destroyed.",
    ftTitle6: "Later stages of tooth decay",
    ftBiobjorn4: `In the case of caries penetrans (penetrating tooth decay), the defect has reached the pulp through the dentin (popularly: "tooth nerve"), so that a connection between the oral cavity and the pulp cavity (cavity in which the pulp is located) has arisen.`,
    ftBio3: "The aim of the treatment is to remove the caries and, depending on the extent of the tooth destruction, to provide it with either a plastic or a ceramic crown (see article on crowns and bridges).",
    ftBio4: "It is very important that several filling materials are tested before treatment. What material does your body respond best to? (See article on material testing)",
    ftBio5: "If the caries has progressed too far, there are 2 options depending on the extent, symptoms, age of the patient and his general physical condition: either a so-called capping (medication and ozone are used to try to preserve the nerve and the body to form a kind of dentin bridge between the nerve and the resulting hole closes) which is very successful in young people under 20 years old or a root canal treatment (see article root canal treatment) in older people or with full symptoms of tooth nerve inflammation which shows up with pain, even very severe pain. A note: the perception of pain and the pain threshold is something individual. Some feel it immediately when caries is still in the early stages, others only at the end when the nerve has already been attacked.",
    ftTitle7: "What to do if the dental caries has progressed too far?",
    ftBiobjorn5: `If the dental caries has progressed too far, there are 2 options depending on the extent, symptoms, age of the patient and his general physical condition: either a so-called capping (medication and ozone are used to try to preserve the nerve and the body to form a kind of dentin bridge between the nerve and the resulting hole closes) which is very successful in young people under 20 years old or a root canal treatment (see article root canal treatment) in older people or with full symptoms of tooth nerve inflammation which shows up with pain, even very severe pain.
        A note: the perception of pain and the pain threshold is something individual. Some feel it immediately when caries is still in the early stages, others only at the end when the nerve has already been attacked.`,
    rcTitle: "Root Canal Treatment",
    rcTitle1: "Previous symptoms:",
    rcBio1: "The tooth hurts or no longer reacts to stimuli, has died, and the surrounding bone is inflamed. The dentist, together with the patient, must decide whether the tooth needs to be extracted or whether root canal treatment should be performed.",
    rcTitle2: "What is root canal treatment?",
    rcBio2: "The nerve canals are cleaned and filled with special dental material. If the nerves in the root area are inflamed, the tooth is first treated with disinfection and then with anti-inflammatory drugs. Only then is the tooth closed again. In addition to the large nerve canals, there are also microcanals in the tooth root that run diagonally to the main canals. Since these are microscopic in size, it is not possible to treat them. Further inflammation can develop in the area, since dead tissue is decomposed here by bacteria and so-called corpse poisons can get into the bloodstream. The immune system is burdened by such toxic substances.",
    rcTitle3: "The following symptoms can occur:",
    rcBio3: "Joint pain, muscle pain, heart muscle problems, flu-like symptoms, cancer is also discussed in certain circles, etc. In the event of a root canal treatment, the optimal filling material is selected using kinesiological tests. Repeated deposits are used to try to minimize any inflammation. It is therefore necessary to strengthen the still living tooth through regular check-ups, homeopathy and ozone treatment and to maintain the vitality of the nerves for as long as possible.",
    cTitle: "Crowns and Bridges",
    cTitle1: "When are dental crowns required?",
    cBio1: "If tooth damage has progressed so far that a filling therapy cannot restore the tooth, a tooth crown is required. The entire visible part of the tooth is redesigned with an approximately 1mm thick crown, which is cemented onto the ground tooth root. However, this is only possible if there are no pathological changes in the root and bone area and the surrounding gums. Otherwise, they must be treated comprehensively beforehand, because a tooth crown is only as good as the foundation underneath. If an entire tooth is lost along with the root, there is the option of filling the resulting gap with a three-unit bridge. A crown is made for each of the teeth adjacent to the gap. These two crowns are connected by a pontic that sits lightly on the gum and fills the gap. Depending on the case, bridges can be an alternative to dental implants",
    cTitle2: "What are the preferred dental crowns and bridges?",
    cBio2: "If the indication is correct, we only prefer all-ceramic crowns and bridges. If the indications do not allow it (excessive grinding), then so-called metal and ceramic crowns with a high gold alloy consisting of 90% gold and platinum (see picture) are used.",
    bTitle: "Prostheses",
    bTitlebjorn: "What are dental prostheses?",
    bBio1: "Dental prostheses are artificial teeth that serve as a replacement for lost natural teeth. Dental prostheses are not fixed in the oral cavity like bridges or implants, but are designed to be removable. In most cases, dentures are much cheaper than fixed dentures. There are different types of prostheses and different combinable possibilities.",
